snippet.textDisplay:
If those tubes are/were made of a plastic, you could scratch a hole with a file or something in the side or the end and drain the water without potentially shattering the tube, too. Alternatively, if a slight jolt was ok to help them move, you could wrap tape around the entire tube to hold it together and lightly crush the end to drain the contaminated water. If the tubes are glass, sufficient tape would either halt the cracking by the cotton ball, or at least hold the structure together enough for the ants to desire moving out.

As for the addition, I think the tower would benefit them most.

snippet.textDisplay: The pink discoloration of the water is probably due to a growth of Serratia marcescens. It's a facultative anaerobic bacteria that has a proclivity for thriving in damp/wet conditions. It's very distinct as it can make water turn pinkish and can also produce pink slimy biofilms on tiles. How bad it will be for ants, I don't know. But it's an causes opportunistic infections for people with weakened immune system.
